##Love in the time of pneumonia: 15 minutes away, it took me 15 days

Micro-signal Zairenjian11

Features, with a calm narrative against the cold | phoenix network produced in the human studio

Phoenix News Client, produced by Phoenix Network Studio on Earth

It's 15 minutes away. It took me 15 days

@ High Winds
COORDINATES: Wuhan & Wuhan

Pneumonia and love have two similarities: First, the body will have signs, people breathing tension, mood swings; Second, no escape, a little attention will catch, but also let people understand the value of life. Pneumonia and love have similar effects in these two respects.

We established our relationship on New Year's Day in 2020, we were both in Wuhan, I met her, Wuhan met new crown pneumonia.

It was during the infatuation stage that the epidemic spread and the city of Wuhan was closed. In order to best protect each other, I did not dare to visit her easily. From January 22 to February 4, we did not meet again.

In the early hours of January 22nd, I went to pick her up from work, and this was the last time we saw each other before the city closed. In the car, she took my hand and fell fast asleep. The street lamp lit her hair from the back of her side, and her short hair, which seemed to have fallen into a state of exhaustion, rested against her cheek. Looking at her in front of me, I couldn't help taking out my mobile phone and taking this photo.

Before the city closure in Wuhan, in order to the health of the elderly at home, she gave up the plan to go home to visit relatives, chose to be isolated in Wuhan alone.

Since the city was sealed, we chat through wechat every day from morning to night, typing, voice, video rotation to. The last person you talk to every day after you wake up and close your eyes is each other. We cheered each other on, lying on our beds in our respective homes, answering 36 questions about love from the psychologist Aalen, alternately reading to each other Wang Haisang's poem I am a place where you wandered; Each other to share all kinds of food dynamic map, appointment after the end of the epidemic to open the belly to eat all over..

She refused to see me during the day by reason, and asked me in her voice late at night when I would meet her.

We don't live far from each other, in Jiang'an District, Florida, and according to current rules in Wuhan, it would be even harder to meet if we lived in different districts. It's a 15-minute drive from my house, and it took me 15 days to get there.

On February 5th, her 14-day quarantine expired, and I know she's been eating instant noodles at home for 15 straight days. I wanted to send her some fresh fruits and vegetables, but was afraid to bring the virus to her here, hesitate again and again, finally determined to see her.

February 5, I was in front of her house, she took this photo, this is our first time after the closure of Wuhan meet.

I grabbed a few things at the supermarket, got on my scooter and headed for her house.

"I really thought you were going to leave your things, " she said.

I held her hand, but did not dare to look at her. I turned my eyes to the picture of the Tankard Buddha in the middle of the living room and muttered, Buddha, I have never done anything wrong, I just wanted to bring her some food on this adventure, please bless us. Don't let me bring the virus to her, and don't let me bring it home.

"You can see my lips are sore, " she said.

"Hmm? " "I was so nervous that I couldn't hear her, so she took her mask off her ear and put her finger in her mouth.

"What are you doing? " I started, involuntarily, as I pulled her hand away, and began to think quickly of the sequence of movements I had made after entering the door: shoes off, coat hanging in the stall, supplies in the kitchen, hands washed three times, i washed my face, and I still wear a mask.

After ruling out all kinds of potential dangers, I said to her: "I came in from the outside, may be infected with the virus, you do too dangerous. "

"You're too nervous. You'll be fine, " she laughed.

Yes, every nerve has been on edge since I walked into the supermarket an hour ago. This was my first trip to the supermarket after I closed the city, and I hadn't been there since academician Zhong Nanshan declared pneumonia a "human-to-human" on January 20. The sight of nearly 10 people lining up shoulder to shoulder in the small enclosed space and more than 10 people shopping around the supermarket made my spine tingle.

After sitting at her house for half an hour, the panic slowly subsided, and my mind told me "it's time to go. ". I got up to say good-bye to her, emotion over reason, embrace, never thought a hug also have the meaning of death together. I wonder when we'll see each other again.

Cycling on the way back, I swept the body when the nervous and panic, in the face of the spring breeze let me with a little bit of pride in the chest, think she can eat a few good meals, suddenly feel like a fire line galloping hero.

The next day, she uncharacteristically posted a picture of herself cooking on her friend's circle, and I knew she was doing it to reassure me.

It was a card given to her on the night of January 1st, and I stuck a stick of her favorite wintersweet on the envelope, containing the lines of Rilke I had hand-copied to her:

Anyone who's looking for you
Wants to test you
The people who found you
Will hold you back
With pictures, with gestures

But I'm willing to understand you
Like the Earth understands you
As I mature,
Your kingdom will mature
I don't want it from you
The vanity of your existence
I know
Time has a name
You have your name

To this day, I really do not know when this epidemic will end. But to walk beside her, to feel life and courage filled with love, never ending.

When I see her in Wuhan,
I think I'll hold her tight and kiss her,
Like a soldier returning home after a war to see his wife.

@ Smell the winter
COORDINATES: Wuhan & Pingxiang

My girlfriend, who lives in Hongshan District, Wuchang, is concerned that although the outbreak is not as severe as in Hankou and Hanyang, there have been more than 20 confirmed cases and deaths in her community. She rarely goes out when her community requires daily temperature monitoring. Occasionally go out, will do a good job of disinfection and isolation.

I'm in Pingxiang, Jiangxi. The outbreak is mild. I'm at peace.

She and I are in good health.

We were both students at the Wuhan University of Technology, and she was a second grader. The delayed opening of the school in Fengcheng, Wuhan, also means that we will experience as long as 2-3 months of long-distance love. Usually we often meet in school, study together to eat, so today's long-distance love is also a small whets.

Since the January 20 explosion in the number of confirmed infections, her mood has been volatile, low and irritable. Her mother had a suspected new coronary, and she was constantly in a panic, but she was fine. During that time, I tried to comfort her with words and use the medical resources of my friends to help her mother with online diagnosis and so on, but I often felt powerless. She also said she was in Wuhan and could not expect others to feel the same way.

Late at night, she is the most emotional time, but I often go to bed early. January 29th was our one-year anniversary, and around 12:40 a.m. , she called. We started video chatting and finally got her to sleep.

We began to avoid talking about the epidemic and to talk about the normal things couples used to talk about. She was very fond of cosmetics, probably due to the influence of the online course, one night she gave me a cosmetic lecture on a whim, I listened to her patiently, also made notes. She hasn't eaten anything delicious for a long time because of the closure of the city, so I said I could do her own eating broadcast. One night, I ordered chicken to go, and I showed it to her on a live video feed.

■ I feed her fried chicken.

During this period, I also began to learn to cook at home, and girlfriend competition cooking skills. The food wasn't as good as usual because of the outbreak, but she also showed me what she cooked every day.

■ On the left is my girlfriend's scrambled eggs and on the right is my scrambled eggs.

I think it's important for two people to be in love, to be tolerant and accepting. I grew up in a small town in Pingxiang, she grew up in Wuhan, and we got different information and grew up in different places. During the outbreak, sometimes I didn't fully understand how she felt. When she's in a bad mood, she's mean, and it makes me feel bad. At times like this, we try to avoid confrontation. More often than not, I don't know how to care for her, and that's when I need her to be inclusive. She was also very understanding, not too much blame.

We talked about what we're GONNA do after the outbreak. Talk about the places we're going, the things we're doing... all of these things make us happy.

When I see her in Wuhan, I think I will hug her tightly and kiss her like a soldier returning home after a war.

I thought maybe when he came back we'd think about getting married

@ Waniko
COORDINATES: Huanggang, Jordan
I'm a media worker, Chinese; Yazan is a Jordanian student, and we've been together for a year and a half. Because of the new crown pneumonia, I was sealed in my native Huanggang, and Yazan was returned to Jordan on the 31st by the Jordanian government.

■ In my hometown, the village also began spraying disinfection water.

Years ago, I left Wuhan on January 20 to return to my native Huanggang. Before leaving, Wuhan had not closed the city, also did not hear to close the city. Yazan was supposed to come back with me, but he caught a cold on January 18 and had a fever and cough. He was worried about cross infection when he went to the hospital, so he chose to stay in Wuhan, rest at home and take medicine, waiting to heal (back then, we didn't know much about the infectiousness of new crowns) .

The siege of Wuhan on January 23rd had a big impact on Yazan's life. During that time, the city's supermarkets were so crowded that Yazan couldn't buy food and spent a few days on the family's leftover noodles and rice. Later, there was no food at home, he lived back to school, the result is also very bad, no food, often hungry at night to wake up only to drink water. Fortunately, after three or four days, he had no fever or headache.

I had planned to go back to his hometown to accompany him in Wuhan, and then in Wuhan together for the New Year. As the city became larger and larger, we gave up our illusions and chatted on wechat every day.

■ Azan is in Jordan.

After 23 days, hear news one after another to say Jordan wants to send a plane to pick up its own citizen to return to the country, but have not fixed the exact date. By the evening of Jan. 31, it was clear that Yazan had left Wuhan for a 12 hour flight back to Jordan.

After arriving in Jordan, Yazan and more than 80 other Jordanian citizens were taken directly to a local hospital for isolation. Tests later confirmed he did not have a new crown, and he was sent home three days later.

To be honest, when he decided to go back, I was angry. I think everyone is in danger because of the epidemic, and he actually abandoned me to go back to China, so there is a bit of estrangement between him, that we are still two people, different hearts. But anger is anger, my heart also hope he can get on the plane back home, safe and sound home.

Two years later, he started taking online classes from elementary school to college. He majored in engineering, but he also took online classes and spent his time in Jordan, where classes begin at 8 a.m. local time at 2 a.m. The schedule of online classes is similar to the normal amount of classes, sometimes two or three, sometimes seven or eight, attendance and homework are included in credit.

■ I'm in Wuhan with Yazan.

If it hadn't been for this outbreak, I would have spent time with him in his small home in Wuhan, making videos, working out, and doing fun things together. After he returned to China, because of the jet lag, we contact less, misunderstanding increased, sometimes quarrel quarrel to break up. I mean, we fought a lot, but we were good, and I took the opportunity to rethink our relationship.

During the epidemic, I think a lot, the future or to cherish the people around us, cherish the freedom of every day. He told me that he would return to Wuhan as soon as Jordan's route to China was resumed.

I thought maybe when he came back we'd think about getting married.

The barbershops are all closed outside,
I had to cut his hair on my dog's grooming machine.

COORDINATES: Wuhan & Wuhan
@Ariel

My boyfriend and I are in Wuhan to prepare a new company, is still in the renovation phase. It was supposed to be finished by the eighth of the year, but now all construction has been halted due to the epidemic, and the opening may have to be postponed. We are a medical industry, years ago prepared useful medical supplies to send friends to the local hospital.

In January, we weren't on high alert for new crown pneumonia, and our families didn't take it seriously until the day before New Year's Eve when the city was declared closed. The New Year's Eve dinner has also been cancelled.

Now my boyfriend and I are fine, no physical discomfort. Parents go home early to prepare for the New Year, road closure can not come back, we can not go back, leaving me and my boyfriend and dog at home.

■ My dog.

We are usually busy working outside, often eat out or order takeout, this closed city forced us to cook by ourselves. Two people do not want to do, do also taste bad, others because at home shut up fat, I and my boyfriend but lost 8 pounds.

I cut my boyfriend's hair.

As a rule, my boyfriend gets his hair cut twice a month. Now the barbershop is closed, so I have to cut his hair. We didn't have the tools, so we ended up using the dog's grooming machine, and guess what.

My boyfriend and I have known each other for nine years, and we were supposed to get married this year, but the process has been pushed back because of the epidemic, and the wedding may be pushed back. As a post-90s, it is really not easy to start a business, before they have been giving themselves a lot of pressure, we basically all year round will not rest a few days. But this outbreak closed the city, we locked up at home, but also to give themselves a holiday. Strive for career progress in the second half of this year, but also to the feelings of many years a perfect account of it.

When I see her in Wuhan, I think I will hug her tightly and kiss her like a soldier returning home after a war.

I thought maybe when he came back we'd think about getting married

I'm a media worker, Chinese; Yazan is a Jordanian student, and we've been together for a year and a half. Because of the new crown pneumonia, I was sealed in my native Huanggang, and Yazan was returned to Jordan on the 31st by the Jordanian government.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
■ In my hometown, the village also began spraying disinfection water.

Years ago, I left Wuhan on January 20 to return to my native Huanggang. Before leaving, Wuhan had not closed the city, also did not hear to close the city. Yazan was supposed to come back with me, but he caught a cold on January 18 and had a fever and cough. He was worried about cross infection when he went to the hospital, so he chose to stay in Wuhan, rest at home and take medicine, waiting to heal (back then, we didn't know much about the infectiousness of new crowns) .

The siege of Wuhan on January 23rd had a big impact on Yazan's life. During that time, the city's supermarkets were so crowded that Yazan couldn't buy food and spent a few days on the family's leftover noodles and rice. Later, there was no food at home, he lived back to school, the result is also very bad, no food, often hungry at night to wake up only to drink water. Fortunately, after three or four days, he had no fever or headache.

I had planned to go back to his hometown to accompany him in Wuhan, and then in Wuhan together for the New Year. As the city became larger and larger, we gave up our illusions and chatted on wechat every day.

Fortunately, after three or four days, he had no fever or headache.

I had planned to go back to his hometown to accompany him in Wuhan, and then in Wuhan together for the New Year. As the city became larger and larger, we gave up our illusions and chatted on wechat every day.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
■ Azan is in Jordan.

After 23 days, hear news one after another to say Jordan wants to send a plane to pick up its own citizen to return to the country, but have not fixed the exact date. By the evening of Jan. 31, it was clear that Yazan had left Wuhan for a 12 hour flight back to Jordan.

After arriving in Jordan, Yazan and more than 80 other Jordanian citizens were taken directly to a local hospital for isolation. Tests later confirmed he did not have a new crown, and he was sent home three days later.

To be honest, when he decided to go back, I was angry. I think everyone is in danger because of the epidemic, and he actually abandoned me to go back to China, so there is a bit of estrangement between him, that we are still two people, different hearts. But anger is anger, my heart also hope he can get on the plane back home, safe and sound home.

Two years later, he started taking online classes from elementary school to college. He majored in engineering, but he also took online classes and spent his time in Jordan, where classes begin at 8 a.m. local time at 2 a.m. The schedule of online classes is similar to the normal amount of classes, sometimes two or three, sometimes seven or eight, attendance and homework are included in credit.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
■ I'm in Wuhan with Yazan.

If it hadn't been for this outbreak, I would have spent time with him in his small home in Wuhan, making videos, working out, and doing fun things together. After he returned to China, because of the jet lag, we contact less, misunderstanding increased, sometimes quarrel quarrel to break up. I mean, we fought a lot, but we were good, and I took the opportunity to rethink our relationship.

During the epidemic, I think a lot, the future or to cherish the people around us, cherish the freedom of every day. He told me that he would return to Wuhan as soon as Jordan's route to China was resumed.

I thought maybe when he came back we'd think about getting married.

The barbershops are all closed outside,
I had to cut his hair on my dog's grooming machine.

@Ariel

My boyfriend and I are in Wuhan to prepare a new company, is still in the renovation phase. It was supposed to be finished by the eighth of the year, but now all construction has been halted due to the epidemic, and the opening may have to be postponed. We are a medical industry, years ago prepared useful medical supplies to send friends to the local hospital.

In January, we weren't on high alert for new crown pneumonia, and our families didn't take it seriously until the day before New Year's Eve when the city was declared closed. The New Year's Eve dinner has also been cancelled.

Now my boyfriend and I are fine, no physical discomfort. Parents go home early to prepare for the New Year, road closure can not come back, we can not go back, leaving me and my boyfriend and dog at home.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
I cut my boyfriend's hair.

As a rule, my boyfriend gets his hair cut twice a month. Now the barbershop is closed, so I have to cut his hair. We didn't have the tools, so we ended up using the dog's grooming machine, and guess what.

My boyfriend and I have known each other for nine years, and we were supposed to get married this year, but the process has been pushed back because of the epidemic, and the wedding may be pushed back. As a post-90s, it is really not easy to start a business, before they have been giving themselves a lot of pressure, we basically all year round will not rest a few days. But this outbreak closed the city, we locked up at home, but also to give themselves a holiday. Strive for career progress in the second half of this year, but also to the feelings of many years a perfect account of it.
